1.2   Motor Axons of the Ventral Root

The accompanying diagram shows a wedge of the spinal cord and the nerves and ganglia associated with it.
In the diagram, identify the multipolar  somatic and visceral motor axons, together in the anterior (ventral) root.
The somatic motor axons are destined to innervate skeletal muscle of the body wall and limbs. This muscle you can move of your own volition.
The visceral motor fibres are destined to innervate smooth muscle, cardiac muscle and glands. These structures are not under your voluntary control.
The ventral root is a peripheral nerve that contains both of these subtypes of motor axons.
